T1  - The staying power of leveraged buyouts
AU  - Kaplan, Steven N.
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 29
IS  - 2
SP  - 287
EP  - 313
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/10/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(91)90004-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X91900044
AB  - This paper documents the organizational status over time of 183 large leveraged buyouts completed between 1979 and 1986. By August 1990, 62% of the LBOs are privately owned, 14% are independent public companies, and 24% are owned by other public companies. The percentage of LBOs returning to public ownership increases over time, with LBOs remaining private for a median time of 6.82 years. The majority of LBOs, therefore, are neither short-lived nor permanent. The moderate fraction of LBO assets owned by other companies implies that asset sales play a role, but are not the primary motivating force in LBO transactions.
